Variable Effect powers can be set to any effect you want within the constraints of their quality (useful, in this case) and any other restraints set by flaws - so, in Amanda's case, her flaw is if/then [must manipulate observable patterns of matter and energy]

Which means they last...forever! Until she dies, is knocked unconscious, runs out of willpower, or changes them for a different power!

So, anyway, you can *reduce* those costs by adding flaws to the power. So, if she, say, created a silver surfboard to fly on that glows brightly?

Meanwhile, if she created a teleport effect, well, firstly, she'd need flaws that make sense for it. The GM can disallow any flaw that doesn't make sense or fit the themes of a power. But, like, we'll say...Obvious for a free gimmie (she vanishes in a bright flash), that's,. like, 6400 yards, or...

3 miles? 

So, she COULD bump that up to 300 miles, then 3000 miles by just spending willpower or by creating more and more esoteric flaws. 

But, like, it's much harder to justify flaws for a teleport, doubly so when you're a character in the game, not a player trying to weasel extra points.
